1️⃣ IPv4 packets on Ethernet
---------------------------
Ethernet frames have a type field (2 bytes) in their 14-byte header.
This type tells the network stack what kind of payload is inside.
For IPv4, the Ethernet type = 0x0800.
This is defined as ETH_P_IP in the Linux headers.
So whenever an Ethernet frame arrives with type = 0x0800, it contains an IPv4 packet.

2️⃣ Protocol handler in Linux kernel
-----------------------------------
The kernel has a network stack that can handle many protocols: IPv4, IPv6, ARP, etc.
For each protocol, there is a protocol handler function — a callback that is called whenever a packet of that protocol arrives.
For IPv4:

static struct packet_type ip_packet_type __read_mostly = {
    .type = cpu_to_be16(ETH_P_IP),  // IPv4 packets
    .func = ip_rcv,                 // function to handle received IPv4 packets
};

.type → specifies Ethernet type (0x0800 for IPv4)
.func → points to the function ip_rcv() that will handle incoming IPv4 packets

3️⃣ Registering the protocol handler
-----------------------------------
During system boot, the IPv4 protocol handler must be registered so the network stack knows:
“Whenever a packet with Ethernet type 0x0800 arrives, call ip_rcv() to process it.”

This is done using:

static int __init inet_init(void)
{
    ...
    dev_add_pack(&ip_packet_type);
    ...
}

dev_add_pack() → adds the ip_packet_type to the kernel’s list of protocol handlers.
inet_init() → initialization function for IPv4; called during boot.

4️⃣ What happens when a packet arrives
-------------------------------------
Ethernet card receives a frame.
The Ethernet driver passes the frame to the network stack.
Network stack looks at the Ethernet type:
  If type = 0x0800 → IPv4 → call ip_rcv()
  If type = something else → call other protocol handler
So ip_rcv() is the function that actually starts processing IPv4 packets.

5️⃣ IPv4 network stack paths
----------------------------
IPv4 protocol has two main paths:
Rx (Receive) path → how incoming IPv4 packets are handled.
  Starts with ip_rcv() → goes through IP header processing, routing decisions, etc.
Tx (Transmit) path → how outgoing IPv4 packets are sent.
  Handled by functions like ip_output() (covered separately).

6️⃣ Summary / Easy Analogy
--------------------------
Ethernet frame → package on the network.
Type field = 0x0800 → label says “this is IPv4.”
Kernel registers handler (ip_rcv) → tells network stack: “if you see 0x0800, call me.”
dev_add_pack() → officially adds this handler to the kernel’s list.
Result: Whenever an IPv4 packet arrives, the kernel automatically sends it to ip_rcv() to handle it.

✅ Key Points
-------------
Ethernet Type 0x0800  → identifies IPv4 packets
ip_packet_type        → structure linking type to handler
ip_rcv()              → function called to process IPv4 packets
dev_add_pack()        → registers the handler in kernel
inet_init()           → initialization function called at boot
Rx path               → handles incoming IPv4 packets
Tx path               → handles outgoing IPv4 packets (later)

